FG-381 — Cert Petition QP Hygiene (Neutral • ≤15 Words)
	•	⚖️ Core Message: The Question Presented must be neutral, short, answerable.
	•	📖 Lesson Content: ≤15 words; no adjectives; frame as a rule question, not facts; mirror in headings.
	•	📝 Assignment: Draft 3 candidate QPs for your petition, each ≤15 words.
	•	✅ Model Response: “Must courts make factor-tied findings before denying preliminary relief?”
	•	💡 Reflection Summary: Panels read QPs first; clarity frames outcomes.
	•	🎨 Visual Concept: A clean question card with a 15-word counter.

⸻

FG-382 — Split Map for Cert (Circuit Positions in One Grid)
	•	⚖️ Core Message: Show the split in one table.
	•	📖 Lesson Content: Table: Circuit • Position • Case cite • Pin; neutral verb (“requires/does not require”); hash the PDF; appendix tab.
	•	📝 Assignment: Build a 6-row split grid for your petition.
	•	✅ Model Response: “9th — requires findings — Winter v. NRDC, 555 U.S. 7 (2008). 2d — not required — Doe v. Smith (2022).”
	•	💡 Reflection Summary: Splits persuade more than adjectives.
	•	🎨 Visual Concept: A map with circuits shaded differently, arrows pointing to a grid.

⸻

FG-383 — Cert Relief Menu (Grant • GVR • Hold)
	•	⚖️ Core Message: Give SCOTUS three doors: Grant, GVR, Hold.
	•	📖 Lesson Content: Grant (full review); GVR (grant, vacate, remand in light of new case); Hold (pending [X]).
	•	📝 Assignment: Draft a 3-line relief menu for your cert petition.
	•	✅ Model Response: “Grant cert. Or GVR in light of [case]. Or hold pending [case].”
	•	💡 Reflection Summary: Three doors cover three instincts.
	•	🎨 Visual Concept: Three arrows leading to one SCOTUS building.

⸻

FG-384 — Appendix Capture Lines (Date • Source • Hash)
	•	⚖️ Core Message: Every appendix doc needs a capture line.
	•	📖 Lesson Content: Footer: “Captured [date] from [source]; SHA-256 ….”; neutral; put on appendix tab front.
	•	📝 Assignment: Add capture lines to 3 tabs and re-export.
	•	✅ Model Response: “Captured 08/19/25 from official FR site; SHA-256 41be22….”
	•	💡 Reflection Summary: Capture proves provenance.
	•	🎨 Visual Concept: A page footer with a fingerprint + calendar chip.

⸻

FG-385 — Cert Petition Summary (≤300 Words, Order-Driven)
	•	⚖️ Core Message: Summaries persuade when they are order-first.
	•	📖 Lesson Content: 3 paragraphs: (1) QP + split; (2) facts neutral + two pins; (3) two-line relief. ≤300 words.
	•	📝 Assignment: Rewrite your summary into 3 paragraphs, ≤300 words.
	•	✅ Model Response: “QP: Must courts…? Split: 2d v. 9th. Facts: court skipped harm (Dkt 18:2; Tab 3 p.2). Relief: grant cert or GVR.”
	•	💡 Reflection Summary: Summaries must be signatures in waiting.
	•	🎨 Visual Concept: Three short blocks stacked with an order strip at bottom.

⸻

FG-386 — Rehearing v. Cert Timeline Card
	•	⚖️ Core Message: Know which door closes when—map both rehearing and cert clocks.
	•	📖 Lesson Content: Rows: Event • Rule • Days • Due date; rehearing (14d), cert (90d from judgment/denial). Add roll-forward.
	•	📝 Assignment: Draft a 2-row timeline with today’s dates.
	•	✅ Model Response: “Rehearing (FRAP 40)—14d → 09/15. Cert (Rule 13)—90d from 09/15 → 12/14.”
	•	💡 Reflection Summary: Clocks persuade clerks and Justices alike.
	•	🎨 Visual Concept: Two parallel timelines with flags.

⸻

FG-387 — Cert Appendix TOC (Neutral, Short, Hashed)
	•	⚖️ Core Message: Keep the appendix TOC neutral and functional.
	•	📖 Lesson Content: TOC lines: “Tab 1 — Judgment (Dkt 88) — SHA-256 …”; no adjectives. One page.
	•	📝 Assignment: Draft 6 neutral TOC lines for your cert appendix.
	•	✅ Model Response: “Tab 2 — Opinion (p.12) — SHA-256 ….”
	•	💡 Reflection Summary: Neutral TOCs reduce suspicion.
	•	🎨 Visual Concept: A binder TOC with hash footers.

⸻

FG-388 — GVR Template (Grant • Vacate • Remand)
	•	⚖️ Core Message: Have a clean GVR order ready.
	•	📖 Lesson Content: Text: “Grant petition; vacate judgment below; remand for further consideration in light of [case].” One page; hash if public.
	•	📝 Assignment: Draft your GVR order with case cite.
	•	✅ Model Response: “Grant petition; vacate judgment; remand for consideration in light of Winter v. NRDC, 555 U.S. 7.”
	•	💡 Reflection Summary: Pre-written orders get signed.
	•	🎨 Visual Concept: A three-step arrow into SCOTUS building.

⸻

FG-389 — Cert Printing & Service Checklist
	•	⚖️ Core Message: SCOTUS filings have strict print/service rules—map them.
	•	📖 Lesson Content: Checklist: 40 copies on 6¾ x 9¼ paper; booklet format; serve all parties; file with affidavit of service.
	•	📝 Assignment: Draft a 6-point print/service checklist with a proof line.
	•	✅ Model Response: “Print 40 booklets; serve respondents; affidavit of service filed.”
	•	💡 Reflection Summary: Physical compliance preserves merits.
	•	🎨 Visual Concept: A stack of booklets with a service stamp.

⸻

FG-390 — Cert Release Note (Docs • Hashes • Mirrors)
	•	⚖️ Core Message: Announce cert filings with a docs-first note.
	•	📖 Lesson Content: 90–120 words: what filed • hashes • mirrors • next step. Post on microsite + index.
	•	📝 Assignment: Draft a release note for your cert petition today.
	•	✅ Model Response: “09/01—Petition for Cert filed (SHA-256 …). 09/02—Appendix filed (SHA-256 …). Mirrors M-1/M-2. Next: response due 10/01.”
	•	💡 Reflection Summary: Public notes create procedural memory.
	•	🎨 Visual Concept: A press release card with fingerprint icons.